				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">French Set Conditions for G.E. Takeover of Alstom</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By ALISSA J. RUBIN, DAVID JOLLY and Liz Alderman			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-06T19:29:16+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 6, 2014 3:29 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 6, 2014 3:29 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/07/business/MONTEBOURG/MONTEBOURG-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/07/business/MONTEBOURG/MONTEBOURG-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/07/business/MONTEBOURG/MONTEBOURG-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002865810" width="592" height="395" alt="Arnaud Montebourg, the French economy minister, during an interview at his office on Tuesday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Arnaud Montebourg, the French economy minister, during an interview at his office on Tuesday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Dmitry Kostyukov for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/french-government-becomes-broker-in-alstom-bid/" data-title="French Set Conditions for G.E. Takeover of Alstom" data-description="French leaders said they would approve G.E.&#039;s bid only if the deal could be completed in a way that protected French workers and the French industrial base.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">PARIS â The French government, caught between concern about jobs at home and the nationâs reputation abroad for meddling in the economy, is plunging more deeply into <a href=" //dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/05/france-says-it-opposes-g-e-s-bit-for-alstom-unit/" title="French Government Opposes G.E. Deal for Alstomâs Electricity Units">the takeover offer for Alstom</a>, one of Franceâs premier companies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Acting almost like investment bankers seeking to extract richer terms, President FranÃ§ois Hollande and his economy minister, Arnaud Montebourg, suggested on Tuesday that they remained open to backing the offer from <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GE&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about General Electric Company">General Electric</a> but laid out a number of conditions that G.E. would have to meet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among them was retaining a headquarters in France, which would presumably give the government leverage to oppose any job cuts or outsourcing of Alstomâs work. They also advocated keeping Alstomâs train-building operations independent and suggested that Alstom acquire G.E.âs train business. And they want to retain some French control of Alstomâs industrial turbine and nuclear power businesses, which G.E. is seeking to buy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are in a strategy of negotiation,â Mr. Montebourg said in an interview. âAnd we want to be heard.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe think we can find a balance between the interests of G.E. and the interests of France,â he added.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last week, Alstomâs board endorsed G.E.âs friendly offer of $13.5 billion for its power generation and transmission businesses. But the French government objected, and the German industrial company Siemens is preparing a competing offer for Alstom.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Seeking to balance political and economic demands, Mr. Hollande and Mr. Montebourg sent coordinated messages on Tuesday that France was not closing the door on the G.E. bid but that the deal would be approved only if it could be completed in a way that protected French workers and the French industrial base.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe want the offers to be improved on jobs,â Mr. Hollande said in an interview broadcast on the television news channel BFM.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is not clear whether the government has the power to stop the deal, but its disapproval would be a clear deterrent. Asked whether he would seek to block a deal he did not agree with, Mr. Montebourg declined to âdiscuss a hypothesis.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The French government, Mr. Montebourg said, is not protectionist and is willing to see French companies absorbed into multinationals. But he said he wanted to set the terms to help Franceâs economic standing and protect its sovereign interests.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That is particularly important with companies like Alstom, Mr. Montebourg said, because it engages in a âsovereign activityâ by manufacturing equipment for the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/energy-environment/atomic-energy/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about nuclear energy.">nuclear energy</a> industry.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The government intervention is merely âeconomic patriotism,â he said, adding that other countries do the same. He described it as part of a new government strategy to revive investment and stimulate the economy while preserving needed jobs. âWe are taking the bull by the horns,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Montebourg sent a letter on Monday to <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/i/jeffrey_r_immelt/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Jeffrey R. Immelt.">Jeffrey R. Immelt</a>, G.E.âs chief executive, saying the government would oppose the G.E. bid as currently structured. But on Tuesday, Mr. Montebourg seemed focused at least as much on getting a better offer from G.E. as on embracing a Siemens offer as an alternative.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens, based in Munich, has proposed a broad swap of its transportation business, which makes high-speed trains, for Alstomâs energy assets, creating a German power giant and a French transportation champion for Europe.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A deal along those lines would leave decision making in France even if the money was largely held across the Rhine, Mr. Montebourg said. That idea is deeply attractive to the French, he said, and âconforms much more closely to our idea of economic sovereignty.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs the choice of being bought by <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Boeing Company">Boeing</a> or choosing to create an Airbus,â Mr. Montebourg said, referring to the American and French-German aviation giants.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although Alstomâs board unanimously accepted the G.E. offer last week, it also agreed to consider the Siemens offer. In the meantime, Mr. Montebourg has been seeking to sway the outcome by negotiating with Mr. Immelt â doing so over the heads of Alstomâs chief executive, Patrick Kron, and its largest investor, the French billionaire Martin Bouygues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his letter to Mr. Immelt, Mr. Montebourg called on G.E. to transfer its transportation businesses â including its freight train and signaling units, valued at $3.9 billion â âto assure a certain global futureâ for Alstom. In the interview on Tuesday, Mr. Montebourg said he hoped that Alstom would come out stronger, whichever deal ended up winning.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alstom has been hurt by weak European demand and by the rise of strong competitors in Asia. Though it is in no immediate danger, it sought out an investment from G.E. as a means of ensuring its long-term survival, because its profits are too low to finance big projects and invest in the next generation of research and development.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Analysts have been mostly supportive of the American offer and skeptical that a deal with Siemens could pass regulatory muster without significant asset sales â and possible job losses â because the French and German companiesâ businesses overlap substantially in some areas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The French governmentâs activist role has also created considerable skepticism about its expertise to choose winners and losers at a time of hyperglobalization.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jean-Luc Gaffard, director of the Department for Research on Innovation and Competition of the French Economic Observatory, noted that Alstom had not grown to the same extent as Siemens and no longer had the economic heft to compete globally.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The governmentâs decision to intervene in the takeover battle is partly an âideologicalâ one, he said, perhaps involving some anti-Americanism. But Mr. Gaffard noted that General Electric âhas a long tradition in France,â where it already employs thousands of workers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI think Patrick Kron is well-informed about the future of Alstom,â he said, âand might know better than the government what is best for it. The bureaucrats have no clear idea about the future of Alstom.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Montebourg, however, does not lack for confidence in his economic judgment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A graduate of the elite Institut dâÃ©tudes politiques de Paris and a former defense lawyer, he has clashed with foreign investors in the past â as when he excoriated <a class="tickerized" title="More information about ArcelorMittal S.A" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MT&amp;inline=nyt-org">ArcelorMittal</a>, the steel giant, for plans to close a blast furnace in eastern France and when he stopped the French video website Dailymotion from falling into the hands of <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Yahoo! Inc" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=YHOO&amp;inline=nyt-org">Yahoo</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most famously, perhaps, he found himself in the spotlight last year in defending France in the face of a tirade by Maurice Taylor Jr., the head of <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Titan International Inc (Illinois)" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TWI&amp;inline=nyt-org">Titan International</a>, an American tire company, who derided French workers, saying they have âone hour for their breaks and lunch, talk for three and work for three.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In each case, Mr. Montebourg said, his actions have been dictated by concerns about the national interest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He acknowledged that Franceâs traditions have shaped a different mind-set about the stateâs role in the economy. âNobody here contests the legitimacy of such decisions,â he said, adding that it was ânaturalâ for the state to get involved when its national interests are at stake.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But he said the idea that France was somehow hostile to foreign capital was contradicted by the fact that there were some 20,000 foreign enterprises employing more than two million people. âFrance is far more open than most other countries in the world,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhat Mr. Hollande is doing with âMade in Franceâ is the same thing that President Obama is trying to do with âonshoringâ in the United States,â Mr. Montebourg said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He pointed to the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States, a federal interagency group that reviews proposals for their national security implications, as evidence that even the United States, with a strongly laissez-faire ethos, was more interventionist in practice than its rhetoric indicates, particularly in areas like energy, ports and other crucial infrastructure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Mr. Hollande, though, not only is this an altruistic effort to save jobs, but it is also a matter of survival for the Socialist government, which has done little to improve the economic climate or pare unemployment, which has hovered at 10 percent for more than two years. The party lost significantly in recent local elections, and Mr. Hollande is more unpopular than any president in recent modern French history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Asked about what the Socialist government would be doing to help revive its standing in elections for the <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Parliament" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_parliament/index.html?inline=nyt-org">European Parliament</a> later this month, in which voters in each country will choose their representatives, Mr. Montebourg said that the governmentâs no to General Electricâs first offer, and the ensuing negotiations, have been popular with the French electorate.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe have the support of public opinion,â he said.</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: May 7, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misstated the school from which Arnaud Montebourg graduated. It was the Institut dâÃ©tudes politiques de Paris, not the Ãcole des Mines de Paris.</div></div><footer class="story-footer">
